   Li-Ling and Thomas, Andrew L. and Hwang, Chin-Feng},
Title = {Genetic diversity of ten black walnut (Juglans nigra L.) cultivars and
   construction of a mapping population},
Journal = {TREE GENETICS \& GENOMES},
Year = {2019},
Volume = {15},
Number = {4},
Month = {AUG},
Abstract = {Black walnut (Juglans nigra L.) nut production stands on the brink of
   potentially great market expansion that can only be realized with
   significant genetic and horticultural improvement, such that commercial
   production becomes feasible. The goal of this study was to incorporate
   microsatellite/simple sequence repeat (SSR) markers to genotype 11
   cultivars and selections, and establish a mapping population from a
   cross of two cultivars, FootballxSparrow. Morphology of these two
   cultivars coupled with phylogenetic analysis supports the notion that a
   cross between them may yield desirable hybrids. Of the 51 SSR markers
   amplified, 23 were polymorphic and useful for genotyping. A selection
   mislabeled as Mintyle was definitively identified as Mintle; therefore,
   the number of cultivars was reduced to 10. Furthermore, seven of the 23
   markers were used to identify 91 intraspecific hybrids
   (FootballxSparrow) resulting from open pollination, thereby establishing
   the first mapping population of black walnut using SSR markers.},
